#import "../../book.typ": *

// ===================== MI SHEBEIRACH · HEALING (PUBLIC PLACEHOLDER) =====================
// This is the committed, public unit for the healing prayer. At Central Reform
// Congregation this moment is sung to the Debbie Friedman / Drorah Setel
// "Mi Shebeirach" (1988), which is under copyright and is NOT included in the
// public repository. The build prefers content/mi-shebeirach-local.typ when it
// exists (see FORK-YOUR-OWN.md §6); otherwise this file is what prints.
// The text below is a fresh rendering of the classical public-domain formula,
// in the book's voice. Communities: license the Friedman/Setel setting from its
// rights holders and put it in your own local file, or make this text your own.
#startprayer("Mi Shebeirach · A Prayer for Healing", "מִי שֶׁבֵּרַךְ", sec: "Concluding", newpage: true)
#rubric([We name, aloud or in our hearts, those in need of healing.])
#stanza("Mi shebeirach avoteinu v'imoteinu, Avraham v'Sara, Yitzchak v'Rivka, Ya'akov, Rachel v'Le'a, Bilha v'Zilpa, hu y'varech virape et kol hacholim.",
  "מִי שֶׁבֵּרַךְ אֲבוֹתֵינוּ וְאִמּוֹתֵינוּ, אַבְרָהָם וְשָׂרָה, יִצְחָק וְרִבְקָה, יַעֲקֹב, רָחֵל וְלֵאָה, בִּלְהָה וְזִלְפָּה, הוּא יְבָרֵךְ וִירַפֵּא אֶת כָּל הַחוֹלִים.")
#stanza("V'yishlach lahem bimheira r'fua sh'leima, r'fuat hanefesh ur'fuat haguf, v'nomar: Amen.",
  "וְיִשְׁלַח לָהֶם בִּמְהֵרָה רְפוּאָה שְׁלֵמָה, רְפוּאַת הַנֶּפֶשׁ וּרְפוּאַת הַגּוּף, וְנֹאמַר: אָמֵן.")
#engn-near("May the One who blessed our fathers and our mothers — Abraham and Sarah, Isaac and Rebecca, Jacob, Rachel and Leah, Bilhah and Zilpah — bless and heal all who are in need of healing. Send them, soon and gently, r'fuah sh'leimah, a complete healing — healing of the spirit and healing of the body — and let us say together: Amen.",
  [Many communities sing this moment to the beloved Mi Shebeirach of Debbie Friedman and Drorah Setel (written 1987; © 1988), which is under copyright and not printed here; communities should license that setting from its rights holders, or set their own words in its place. What stands here is the classical formula — a blessing once spoken over individuals at the Torah, turned toward the whole community's care for its own.])
